Welcome to the=C2=A01,716=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined=
 us since last Monday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0141,332=
 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:=20
=F0=9F=8E=A7 To listen to the audio edition, head over to Spotify [https://=
substack.com/redirect/8a8a7a1e-2da8-4a43-a4a9-e5f4cc4c6a41?u=3D16283549] or=
=C2=A0Apple Podcasts [https://substack.com/redirect/824c0f7c-7562-436d-afbb=
-12f3e9ab8dd1?u=3D16283549].
This week=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Causal [https:=
//substack.com/redirect/b4701745-b085-4568-80d1-b31e32208fc0?u=3D16283549]
Our mission at Not Boring is to make the world more optimistic =E2=80=93 bu=
t your business can=E2=80=99t make the world better without strong planning=
=2E That=E2=80=99s where Causal [https://=
substack.com/redirect/b4701745-b085-=
4568-80d1-b31e32208fc0?u=3D16283549] comes in.
Causal [https://substack.com/redirect/b4701745-b085-4568-80d1-b31e32208fc0?=
u=3D16283549] is a spreadsheet built for number-crunching =E2=80=94 financi=
al modeling, business planning, but really anything involving calculations.=
 It's like Excel minus the arcane formulas (no more Sheet1!$E$4 or VLOOKUPs=
), plus live data integrations (accounting systems, CRMs, etc), and easily =
shareable dashboards.
Now more than ever, every company needs a solid financial model to steer th=
e ship. I've worked with the Causal team to create the Startup Suite =E2=80=
=94 4 template models for early stage startups:
B2B SaaS revenue model [https://substack.com/redirect/bad4d123-2b1e-4ed3-96=
d3-5bbf31ef5e62?u=3D16283549]
Headcount + hiring plan [https://substack.com/redirect/9cc1d196-ab0a-46e4-8=
cac-62142cfef317?u=3D16283549]
Profit & Loss + cash projection [https://substack.com/redirect/c7662178-e9a=
e-42dc-b0ef-9a6e94d73275?u=3D16283549]
Employee compensation calculator [https://substack.com/redirect/bcc4e9f1-8d=
97-4df6-b11a-a812d8f559ee?u=3D16283549]
They've put together detailed video walkthroughs for each model in their do=
cumentation [https://substack.com/redirect/b46c01a4-9c84-42cb-9ab7-94b9594d=
9cf9?u=3D16283549]. Use one of my templates above as a starting point, sign=
-up to and just play around, or win some brownie points with your finance/p=
lanning team by sending them the Not Boring Causal link [https://substack.c=
om/redirect/b4701745-b085-4568-80d1-b31e32208fc0?u=3D16283549].
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Monday! Hope you stayed cool this weekend. It was a balmy 95 here in =
Brooklyn; perfect weekend to stay inside and write.=20
Over the past few months, I=E2=80=99ve noticed a vibe shift online: the con=
versation seems to be getting more negative, aggressive, and polarized. Tod=
ay=E2=80=99s piece is an attempt to unpack why so many people are talking p=
ast each other, why it=E2=80=99s damaging, and what to do about it. It=E2=
=80=99s not as upbeat as a lot of Not Boring pieces, but I think addressing=
 this issue is crucial to unlocking progress. =20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Amplified Tribalism [https://substack.com/redirect/e6df4f8d-2c89-415a-a539-=
591e46b942a3?u=3D16283549]
(Click this link =F0=9F=91=86 to jump right to your browser)
You won=E2=80=99t find many people who love the internet more than me. My w=
hole career is based on the internet. I spend way too much time on Twitter.=
 When people have criticized Twitter for being a dark place full of trolls =
and hate, I=E2=80=99ve defended it. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s not been my exp=
erience,=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99d retort, =E2=80=9CMost of the interactions I h=
ave on Twitter are thoughtful and fun!=E2=80=9D I wrote The Great Online Ga=
me [https://substack.com/redirect/c3e99ca9-af02-4c5c-b9f8-e3fc077795ed?u=3D=
16283549] and meant it.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not feeling that love as much recently.=C2=A0
Maybe the bear market and the potential of recession is bringing out bad vi=
bes. Maybe everyone=E2=80=99s a little bit hungover from a couple of years =
of excess and upside. Maybe it=E2=80=99s just that we=E2=80=99ve just spent=
 too much time online together over the past couple of years and it=E2=80=
=99s starting to feel cramped.=C2=A0
The early COVID period online was like Episode 1 of any season of The Real =
World. Everyone shows up to the house all excited to meet new people and em=
bark on a wild adventure together.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CEveryone here is so funny and smart and hot! Let=E2=80=99s do shot=
s! We are going to have the BEST TIME EVER!!! <3=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
COVID was and remains terrible [insert all of the bad things], but there wa=
s something catalyzing about the early days of the pandemic. In Conjuring S=
cenius [https://substack.com/redirect/4e4021ce-01dd-471d-9e51-25fdca7f468a?=
u=3D16283549], I wrote that, =E2=80=9CWhen it is all said and done, I belie=
ve that historians will look back at the Coronavirus pandemic as the greate=
st catalyst for progress and creativity in human history.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That was a crazy claim to make in May 2020, but there were three reasons I =
thought it might be true:=C2=A0
It served as the previously-absent, globally-catalyzing event for the inter=
net generation.
People across the globe banded together, united by a common mission: to fig=
ht the spread of this disease.
Having been forced to interact almost exclusively online for an extended pe=
riod, people are creating new tools, processes, and social norms that make =
collaborating online more like collaborating in-person.=C2=A0
I thought that those three factors might be enough to precipitate the first=
 global scenius, which musician Brian Eno described as =E2=80=9Cthe intelli=
gence and the intuition of a whole cultural scene. It is the communal form =
of the concept of the genius.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Think back to that time. There was fear and fighting, but most of it was fo=
cused on the pandemic and, in America, Trump. Outside of those two topics (=
and they=E2=80=99re very big ones, but concentrated) the vibes online were =
incredibly positive. People experimented with new ways to connect, share in=
formation, have fun, and create online. Technology, from Zoom to mRNA, was =
viewed as a positive force. People, unlocked, often unwillingly [https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/18c77f79-407e-466c-af28-23139b95c5c2?u=3D16283549], fro=
m their old jobs, tried new things, and generally, people were supportive o=
f whatever they pursued.=C2=A0
In a 2008 essay [https://substack.com/redirect/12f91cea-5601-4335-9ce6-9937=
65add41e?u=3D16283549], Kevin Kelly laid out the four factors that have his=
torically nurtured scenius:
Mutual appreciation =E2=80=94 Risky moves are applauded by the group, subtl=
ety is appreciated, and friendly competition goads the shy. Scenius can be =
thought of as the best of peer pressure.
Rapid exchange of tools and techniques =E2=80=94 As soon as something is in=
vented, it is flaunted and then shared. Ideas flow quickly because they are=
 flowing inside a common language and sensibility.
Network effects of success =E2=80=94 When a record is broken, a hit happens=
, or breakthrough erupts, the success is claimed by the entire scene. This =
empowers the scene to further success.
Local tolerance for the novelties =E2=80=94 The local =E2=80=9Coutside=E2=
=80=9D does not push back too hard against the transgressions of the scene.=
 The renegades and mavericks are protected by this buffer zone.
All four were present on the early COVID internet, and to me, it felt like =
we could finally unlock that idea of scenius from its geographic boundaries=
 and bring it to a global scale.=C2=A0
But if you=E2=80=99ve watched The Real World, you=E2=80=99ll know that the =
novelty and excitement of being thrown into unusual circumstances with a gr=
oup of strangers fades quickly. Humans gonna human.=C2=A0
By like Episode 3, relationships and cliques and romances and rivalries sta=
rt to form, and the housemates need to get jobs and work together, and the =
producers feed them booze, and they=E2=80=99re stuck with each other all=E2=
=80=A6 the=E2=80=A6 time. The housemates stop being polite, and start being=
 REAL.=C2=A0
It feels like we=E2=80=99ve turned that corner on the internet, maybe a whi=
le back. I=E2=80=99m ready to declare my dream of a COVID-fueled Global Onl=
ine Scenius dead.=C2=A0
Like Real World housemates, the online housemates have retreated into tribe=
s and cliques. People are sick of each other. People are no longer willing =
to support, or at least tolerate, the wild ideas they were willing to suppo=
rt or tolerate when people had nothing better to do. Instead of concentrati=
ng attention and angst on COVID and Trump, attention and angst are once aga=
in fragmented. Everyone is talking past each other.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s been a vibe shift [https://substack.com/redirect/359dcdda-2=
8ec-4416-a3f7-b0cf45828869?u=3D16283549]. It=E2=80=99s not as innocuous as =
who=E2=80=99s wearing and listening to what. It=E2=80=99s a shift from assu=
ming the best in others to assuming the worst. I=E2=80=99m worried it has d=
angerous implications for our ability to make progress.=C2=A0
Some of it is outright fighting, name calling, and the like. There are some=
 truly miserable people on the internet who wake up every day and make it t=
heir mission to dunk on people to boost their followings and sense of self-=
worth. But a lot of it just seems to be people picking tribes, identifying =
with certain worldviews and sticking with them no matter what. Jonathan Hai=
dt was [https://substack.com/redirect/4107e6d5-cf30-4c28-8023-20696a2f535e?=
u=3D16283549] right [https://substack.com/redirect/4107e6d5-cf30-4c28-8023-=
20696a2f535e?u=3D16283549].
You can find signs of the shift everywhere:=C2=A0
Green activists and nuclear proponents yelling past each other when they ul=
timately, ostensibly, want the same thing=C2=A0
NIMBYs versus YIMBYs=C2=A0
The Woke Mob versus anyone who accidentally says something in the wrong way=
 or without the right caveats=C2=A0
Tech people versus non-tech people=C2=A0
Web3 versus Web2 (or crypto vs. anti-crypto)
Remote versus in-office
Left versus right=C2=A0
The list goes on and on. It seems as if the default stance is that anyone o=
n =E2=80=9Cthe other team=E2=80=9D is definitely wrong, potentially stupid,=
 probably malicious, and maybe even criminal. Without a common goal or comm=
on enemy, everyone is talking past each other.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t want to make this a crypto piece, but it=E2=80=99s what=E2=
=80=99s in my feed, and the conversation around regulation in crypto over t=
he weekend provides a clear example of what I=E2=80=99m talking about.=C2=
=A0
In January, Prof G captured [https://substack.com/redirect/c10dcd4e-b002-4c=
05-bf68-cd1c7f729eda?u=3D16283549] the anti-crypto camp=E2=80=99s popular (=
but false) perception of the pro-crypto camp=E2=80=99s view on regulation. =
He wrote that the decentralization narrative =E2=80=9Cis a false god evange=
lized by high priests who pass collection plates the size of Mars and admon=
ish regulation as heresy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I got sucked in and wrote a rebuttal [https://substack.com/redirect/f63916f=
6-5d29-491d-beb1-cf7fdf17d7dc?u=3D16283549], pointing out that anyone serio=
us I=E2=80=99d spoken to in crypto desperately wanted sensible and clear re=
gulation so they could do their jobs without having to worry about going to=
 jail.=C2=A0
Recently, the All-In Podcast has started pushing a narrative that=E2=80=99s=
 been pervasive on Crypto Twitter for a year that web3 VCs are taking advan=
tage of the lack of regulation to dump tokens on retail. Cobie provides the=
 best overview in this essay [https://substack.com/redirect/12b97c57-4df7-4=
539-ad43-0e3f5f0eb1ad?u=3D16283549] =E2=80=93 essentially, shitty, short-te=
rm VCs do this, legitimate, long-term VCs don=E2=80=99t. But Jason and All-=
In gleefully paint everyone with the same brush and root for people to go t=
o jail.=C2=A0
This weekend, FTX founder and CEO Sam Bankman-Fried tweeted =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=
=80=99d love to be further regulated!=E2=80=9D,=C2=A0 expressing the common=
 view among anyone serious in the space:
And the response wasn=E2=80=99t, =E2=80=9COK, cool, so we all agree? More r=
egulation? Great!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
It was, =E2=80=9COf course they want more regulation! Those in power always=
 want more regulation because it makes it harder for new entrants to compet=
e with them!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Others in the crypto extreme chimed in and said, =E2=80=9CNo, we don=E2=80=
=99t want regulation. Otherwise, we=E2=80=99ll just end up with banking 2.0=
,=E2=80=9D ignoring the reality of the situation. And on and on it will go.=
 It=E2=80=99s exhausting.
Again, I don=E2=80=99t want to make this a crypto piece. It=E2=80=99s just =
a very clear example of two sides talking past each other and digging in on=
 their side instead of trying to find a common ground. You can find similar=
 back-and-forths almost anywhere you look.=C2=A0
The Russian invasion of Ukraine brought to light some of the silliness in t=
he environmental movement, which impacts politicians=E2=80=99 very real dec=
isions, like railing against nuclear power. Faced with the very real threat=
 of energy shortages, the EU parliament backed rules labeling gas and nucle=
ar as =E2=80=9Cgreen=E2=80=9D for investment purposes. Greta was not happy.=
=C2=A0
At the time of writing, 1,793 people have quote tweeted that tweet, most po=
inting out how Greta=E2=80=99s anti-nuclear stance was unrealistic, inconsi=
stent, and led to things like the EU turning to coal as nuclear plants shut=
 down. This battle, too, will go back and forth, exhaustingly.=C2=A0
The internet, and social media specifically, aren=E2=80=99t entirely to bla=
me =E2=80=93 tribalism and disagreement go back as far as humanity =E2=80=
=93 but social media amplifies, polarizes, and distorts. Everyone with an i=
nternet connection, regardless of knowledge or motivation, can weigh in, re=
tweet, dunk, and argue for argument=E2=80=99s sake. Many choose to play The=
 Great Online Game on dumb mode, fanning flames just to feel something, and=
 it=E2=80=99s pushing sides further apart and further from positive action.=
=C2=A0
Jonathan Haidt was right when he wrote of the social media game in Why the =
Past 10 Years of American Life Have Been Uniquely Stupid [https://substack.=
com/redirect/2fcd1c05-ab9b-4dcb-a16e-0187803c352e?u=3D16283549]:
This new game encouraged dishonesty [https://substack.com/redirect/604b07d4=
-189b-4515-93d8-c0bad7054878?u=3D16283549] and mob dynamics: Users were gui=
ded not just by their true preferences but by their past experiences of rew=
ard and punishment, and their prediction of how others would react to each =
new action.
(I highly recommend reading his whole essay [https://substack.com/redirect/=
2fcd1c05-ab9b-4dcb-a16e-0187803c352e?u=3D16283549] if you haven=E2=80=99t y=
et.)
I=E2=80=99m neither innocent nor immune here.=C2=A0
I kinda dunked on someone [https://substack.com/redirect/1df738b8-f983-4d19=
-9d49-788ff18f1540?u=3D16283549] this weekend, and I justified it to myself=
 because he=E2=80=99d dunked on me in the past. I don=E2=80=99t love that I=
 did that; it=E2=80=99s not my natural stance. I love a good debate, but th=
ere=E2=80=99s a pretty clear line between a good faith conversation and try=
ing to score points for your team. I=E2=80=99ve noticed that as I=E2=80=99v=
e come under fire, I=E2=80=99ve dug in my heels.=C2=A0
More worryingly, I can feel the vibe shift impacting my creativity and writ=
ing. If I=E2=80=99m being honest, I don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99ve been a=
s good at writing Not Boring since I went viral for a dumb answer on crypto=
 use cases [https://substack.com/redirect/39685974-6957-4d26-93dd-70f1d2182=
96d?u=3D16283549].=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s hard to parse whether it=E2=80=99s that the whole incident was=
 personal and internet-scale =E2=80=93 there was a fucking Atlantic [https:=
//substack.com/redirect/89fa24d6-c716-4b38-852c-b4db28e66739?u=3D16283549] =
article [https://substack.com/redirect/89fa24d6-c716-4b38-852c-b4db28e66739=
?u=3D16283549] about it =E2=80=93 or whether it just coincided with the gen=
eral vibe shift, market crash, and boiling point.=C2=A0
Either way, it=E2=80=99s been harder to come up with ideas. Harder to find =
the excitement that I usually have when I seize on a topic and work to unde=
rstand everything about it. Harder to feel great when I hit send, knowing t=
hat there are a bunch of people on the internet who will comb through it to=
 find anything dumb (and there=E2=80=99s always something dumb!).=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not that I=E2=80=99m scared to write, or depressed, or living =
in a constant state of worry. I=E2=80=99m happy and optimistic 99% of the t=
ime. It just feels like there=E2=80=99s a governor on my creativity and exc=
itement, a low-grade thing buzzing in the background that gets amplified an=
y time I go on Twitter. Sometimes when I=E2=80=99m sitting here writing on =
a sunny summer Saturday, I wonder: what=E2=80=99s the point? People who agr=
ee with me will agree with me, and people who disagree aren=E2=80=99t going=
 to change their mind.=C2=A0
In the grand scheme of things, my creativity and excitement levels are unim=
portant. I bring it up because, while it=E2=80=99s very apparent that all o=
f this amplified tribalism leads to gridlock on a larger scale =E2=80=93 in=
 what politicians are able to propose and pass, in what gets built and how =
fast =E2=80=93 experiencing it first-hand makes me concerned that there are=
 probably a lot of people in more important positions who have that creativ=
e and productive governor on.=C2=A0
Haidt describes something similar happening to America=E2=80=99s institutio=
ns in the essay:=C2=A0=C2=A0
A mean tweet doesn=E2=80=99t kill anyone; it is an attempt to shame or puni=
sh someone publicly while broadcasting one=E2=80=99s own virtue, brilliance=
, or tribal loyalties. It=E2=80=99s more a dart than a bullet, causing pain=
 but no fatalities.
=E2=80=A6 This, I believe, is what happened to many of America=E2=80=99s ke=
y institutions in the mid-to-late 2010s. They got stupider en masse because=
 social media instilled in their members a chronic fear of getting darted.
He was referring specifically to institutions that lost their backbone =E2=
=80=93 their willingness to stand up for their people in the face of social=
 media heat and their acceptance of dissenting views internally =E2=80=93 a=
nd became less effective, dumber, in the process. David Deutsch=E2=80=99s P=
rinciple of Optimism states that =E2=80=9CAll evils are caused by insuffici=
ent knowledge.=E2=80=9D Pushing away knowledge to appease a mob is anti-opt=
imistic.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Not Boring isn=E2=80=99t a newsletter about politics or America=E2=80=99s i=
nstitutions. I=E2=80=99m writing this because the darts hit startups, too, =
and innovators more broadly.=C2=A0=C2=A0
To read about how amplified tribalism is impacting startups and depressing =
progress, and how we might get out of it=E2=80=A6=20
Thanks to Dan [https://substack.com/redirect/7af1f631-a557-4b71-93bc-f4d0d6=
4e9061?u=3D16283549] and Puja for editing!
Have a great week, and see you back here later this week.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

